# =============================================================================
# backend/.dockerignore
# =============================================================================
# Controls which files are sent to the Docker build context.
# Docker reads this before COPY instructions in the Dockerfile.
# Excluding files here:
#   1. Prevents secrets leaking into image layers
#   2. Reduces build context size (faster builds, smaller images)
#   3. Stops local dev state from polluting the production container
# =============================================================================


# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# .env  ← SECRET LEAK PREVENTION (CRITICAL)
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Contains live API keys and the SECRET_KEY used to sign JWTs.
# If baked into a Docker image layer, it can be extracted by anyone with
# access to the image — even after deletion in a later layer.
# Secrets must always come from Render environment variables at runtime,
# never from files baked into the image.
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
.env
*.env


# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# *.db  ← DATA LEAK + STALE STATE PREVENTION
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# money_manager.db is the local SQLite database containing real development
# data (users, transactions, accounts). Copying it into the image would:
#   - Ship local user data into the production container (data leak)
#   - Overwrite the production database path on every build
#   - Make the container image non-reproducible between developers
# The database is created fresh at container startup via SQLAlchemy's
# Base.metadata.create_all() call in main.py.
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
*.db
*.sqlite
*.sqlite3


# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# .venv/ and venv/  ← IMAGE BLOAT PREVENTION
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Local Python virtual environments can be 200–500 MB.
# The Dockerfile installs all dependencies cleanly inside the container using:
#   pip install --no-cache-dir -r requirements.txt
# Copying local venvs into the image would:
#   - Massively bloat the image (slower pushes, slower Render deploys)
#   - Include platform-specific compiled binaries built for Windows/macOS
#     that will not run on the Linux container
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
.venv/
venv/


# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# **/__pycache__/  ← IMAGE BLOAT + CACHE POISONING
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Python bytecode cache directories are auto-generated by the interpreter
# for the specific Python version and platform that compiled them.
# Including them causes:
#   - Unnecessary image bloat (often 10–30 MB across a large project)
#   - Cache invalidation issues if the container Python version differs
#     from the developer's local version (silent import of stale bytecode)
# Python regenerates __pycache__ on first import inside the container anyway.
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
**/__pycache__/
*.pyc
*.pyo
*.pyd


# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# uploads/  ← EPHEMERAL USER DATA EXCLUSION
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# The uploads/ directory holds user-uploaded receipts and files generated
# during local development. Including it would:
#   - Ship local dev files (possibly containing real personal data) into prod
#   - Create a false impression that uploads persist across deploys
#     (Render's ephemeral filesystem wipes this on every redeploy)
# On Render, a Persistent Disk should be mounted at /app/uploads if file
# persistence is required.
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
uploads/


# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# scratch_*.py  ← DEV TOOLING EXCLUSION
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# One-off development scripts used to inspect/seed/debug the local database.
# These are not part of the application and must not run in production
# (they contain hardcoded queries, debug prints, and DB manipulation logic).
# Examples currently present:
#   scratch_cats.py, scratch_db.py, scratch_debug_delete.py, scratch_users.py
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
scratch_*.py


# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# test_*.py  ← TEST SUITE EXCLUSION
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Unit and integration test files have no place in a production image:
#   - They add unnecessary size to the container
#   - Some tests (e.g. test_llm_mock.py) set environment variables that
#     could interfere with production config if accidentally executed
#   - Test frameworks (pytest etc.) are not in requirements.txt so tests
#     would fail to run inside the container anyway
# Run tests in CI (e.g. GitHub Actions), not inside the production image.
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
test_*.py


# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Additional safe exclusions
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

# Dockerfile itself — not needed at runtime inside the container
Dockerfile

# The example env file — documentation only, not needed at runtime
.env.example

# Git metadata — large and irrelevant inside the container
.git/
.gitignore

# Editor and IDE config directories
.vscode/
.idea/
*.swp
*.swo

# macOS filesystem artifacts
.DS_Store

# Windows filesystem artifacts
Thumbs.db
